The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence (AI) technologies has led to their widespread adoption across numerous domains, from assistant agents (e.g., ACT-1, from Adept AI111ACT-1:[https://www.adept.ai/blog/act-1](https://www.adept.ai/blog/act-1)) and software development (e.g., Devin, from Cognition Lab222Devin:[https://www.cognition-labs.com/introducing-devin](https://www.cognition-labs.com/introducing-devin)) to healthcare> (Singhal et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib144)> )
and finance> (Zheng et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib187)> )
. However, the success of AI models heavily relies on the availability of large, diverse, and high-quality datasets for training and evaluation. Acquiring such datasets can be a significant challenge due to data scarcity> (Babbar and Schölkopf, [> 2019
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib11)> )
, privacy concerns> (Abay et al., [> 2019
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib1)> )
, and the sheer cost of data collection and annotation> (Gilardi et al., [> 2023b
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib51)> )
. Pessimists predict that we will run out of fresh text data in 2050 and image data in 2060> (Villalobos et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib157)> )
.
Synthetic data has emerged as a promising solution to address these challenges> (Nikolenko, [> 2021
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib113)> )
. Synthetic data refers to artificially generated data that mimics the characteristics and patterns of real-world data, but is created through algorithms> (Saxton et al., [> 2019
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib134)> )
, generative models> (Borisov et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib16)> ; Meng et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib108)> )
, or even simulations> (Vezhnevets et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib156)> ; Liu et al., [> 2023c
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib99)> )
, rather than being directly created by humans. By leveraging synthetic data, we can not only overcome the limitations of real-world data but also unlock the potential to develop more robust, reliable, and fair AI models> (Lucini, [> 2021
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib102)> ; Lu et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.07503v1#bib.bib101)> )
.
